[The number of countries and territories reporting confirmed cases of COVID-19 to WHO remains at 215. This includes 19 countries (including 4 territories) from the Western Pacific region, 61 countries (including 7 territories) from the European region, 10 countries from the South-East Asia region, 22 countries (including 1 territory) from the Eastern Mediterranean region, 54 countries (including 19 territories) from the Americas region, and 49 countries (including 2 territories) from the African region.

In the 24 hours since the last WHO update:
------------------------------------------
The Americas region reported 45 015 new cases (51.8% of the global newly reported cases), and 3123 deaths (63.2%) for this 24-hour period. Of the newly confirmed cases in the region, 46.3% were reported by the USA, followed by Brazil 31%, Peru 9.5%, Mexico 5.4%, and Canada 2.9%. The Americas region is maintaining its status as having the highest cumulative case count of the 6 WHO regions, with the European region as the 2nd-highest region.

The European region reported 22 150 new cases (25.5% of the global newly reported cases) and 1446 deaths (29.3%). Russia reported 41.5% of the newly confirmed cases in the region, followed by the UK 16.1%, Turkey 7.7%, Belarus 4.3%, Italy 3.6%, Spain 2.9%, and Sweden at 2.8%.

The Eastern Mediterranean region reported 10 479 new cases (12.1% of the global newly reported cases) and 143 deaths (2.9%). Saudi Arabia reported 22.0 % of the regional newly reported cases, followed by Iran at 20.0 %, Pakistan 15.1%, Qatar 11.0 %, Kuwait 8.4%, the United Arab Emirates at 7.1%, and Oman at 3.9%.

The African region reported 2271 new cases (2.6% of the global newly reported cases) and 44 deaths (0.9%). South Africa reported 34.6% of the newly reported cases in the region in the past 24 hours, followed by Nigeria 12.7%, Algeria 8.3%, Senegal at 5.3 %, and Ghana 4.8%.

The Western Pacific region reported 1171 new cases (1.3% of the global newly reported cases) and 33 deaths (0.6%). Singapore reported 67.7% of the newly reported cases, followed by the Philippines 18.4% and Japan 3.7%. Removing Singapore from the denominator has the Philippines at 56.8%, Japan 11.6%, Malaysia at 9.5, Australia at 7.9% and Viet Nam at 6.6%.

The South-East Asia region reported 5741 new cases (6.6% of the global newly reported cases) and 151 deaths (3.0%). India reported 69.2% of newly reported cases, followed by Bangladesh 20.9% and Indonesia 8.5%. These 3 countries make up 95.7% of all reported cases in the region. Removing India from the denominator, Bangladesh represents 67.9% of the newly reported cases, Indonesia 27.7%, and the Maldives 2.8%.

Figure 2. Epidemic curve of confirmed COVID-19 cases, by date of report and WHO region, 30 Dec 2019 through 16 May 2020, at the source URL above, is an excellent representation of the epidemic starting in the Western Pacific, transitioning to multiregional activity as the virus travelled. Europe has decreased. The Americas is increasing, as is South-East Asia.

A somewhat repetitive but necessary reminder: It is clear that the number of reported confirmed cases differs from different reporting websites and is somewhat a function of time of day the website is updated. For example, I note the time we've accessed the Johns Hopkins' CSSE or Worldometer website, but by the time the post is actually finished with the editing process, those numbers have, at times, significantly changed. Case counting is clearly a moving target, and depending upon when the website updates, the numbers may be different. I try to start each post with the latest figures for the calendar day (the Johns Hopkins CSSE or Worldometer table) and close with the figures from the start of the calendar day (the WHO tables), defining the calendar day as DST (now GMT-4). - Mod.UBA

